---
description: Next.js frontend rules (web — Admin + Dashboard; API consumers use backend directly)
globs: frontend/**, src/**, app/**, components/**, lib/**, hooks/**
---

This rule applies to the **web** frontend only. API consumers use the FastAPI backend directly; see .cursor/rules/12-interfaces-admin-user-mobile.mdc.

Frontend stack (per CLAUDE.md):
- Next.js 14 (App Router), React 18, Tailwind CSS 3, shadcn/ui, Zustand, React Query, Socket.IO client

Frontend rules:
- Prefer TypeScript for all frontend logic; strict mode, no `any`; prefer `interface` for objects.
- Keep components small, reusable, and focused.
- Keep presentation separate from business/data-fetching logic.
- Use hooks, services, or server actions appropriately based on project style.
- Handle loading, error, and empty states explicitly.
- Preserve design consistency and naming consistency.
- Support real-time updates (WebSocket/Socket.IO) for live stream status and moderation alerts.
- **Two UIs in one app:** **Admin** (e.g. `/admin/*`) and **Dashboard/User** (e.g. `/`, `/dashboard`, `/videos`, `/moderation`, `/live`, `/analytics`); use role-based routing and layout; shared design system and API client.

Product-area alignment (see docs/PRD.md and CLAUDE.md):
- **Admin (web):** Policy management, system monitoring, API keys, tenant/org settings.
- **Dashboard (web):** Videos (list, detail, upload), moderation (queue, review, policies), live streams, analytics, settings.
- **API consumers:** Not covered by this rule; they use REST/WebSocket API.

Preferred frontend structure (per CLAUDE.md):
- frontend/src/app/            (layout, page, (auth), dashboard, videos, moderation, live, api)
- frontend/src/components/     (ui, layout, video, moderation, analytics, live)
- frontend/src/hooks/
- frontend/src/stores/
- frontend/src/lib/
- frontend/src/types/
- frontend/tests/

UI/UX rules:
- Use accessible markup and semantic HTML.
- Prefer reusable design system components (shadcn/ui).
- Avoid oversized page components.
- Avoid embedding complex API logic directly inside visual components unless already established.

State/data rules:
- Keep API clients centralized (lib/api.ts, socket).
- Normalize repeated API access patterns.
- Handle auth state carefully.
- Validate critical inputs on both client and server.

Do not:
- Mix many responsibilities into one component.
- Hardcode API URLs in components.
- Duplicate UI patterns that should be shared.
- Put admin-only flows in a separate mobile/partner app (admin is web only).
